<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:306236">musiclady</a>, <a href="/user/uid:972826">jsb16</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>Infuriate me. What do you do for a living, Be Skeptical? Are you universally competent and wise? If not; if you simply have experience that your neophyte colleagues don't, which makes you better at many aspects of your job; don't you agree that you really need to be replaced by someone who is younger, more energetic, willing to work for less money, and perfectly happy to change jobs every couple of years?</p>
<p>I am reminded of a poster on another site who blamed teachers for the suicide of a teenager who was bullied on Facebook. Because (I paraphrase, but you might be astonished to find how slightly) "every teacher is obligated to be aware of the social, familial, and personal &nbsp;lives of the 75-100 students (in high schools, at least) that he or she teaches." Including their Facebook activities, apparently. He continued, "Teachers who can't handle that should be summarily fired."</p>
<p>I love my job, which involves teaching kids who have IQs in the 68-75 range (but are expected to pass the same standardized tests that the AP and Honors kids take). Guess why I'm working on an M.S. in Health Information Technology? And why, after ten years of good-to-excellent performance reviews, I'll be quitting as soon as the degree is completed?</p>
<p>If I have misunderstood your "myth of the universally competent yet wise teacher" comment, I sincerely apologize; and I'm not really directing this rant at you. &nbsp;There may be a few of those out there, but no one is claiming that about all veteran teachers. A lot of people, however, are buying into the myth of the "hidebound, resistant to change, disaffected, indifferent, veteran teachers who needs to be summarily replaced," and I'm very tired of it.</p>

  </div>
