<li id="c296">
  <div class="cx" id="cx51231816">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">The problem is when people start saying</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1234916/51231816#c296?mode=alone;showrate=1#c296">1+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:15174">elfling</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>that a certain percentage of teachers--whether experienced or new--are bad. &nbsp;It differs by location.</p>
<p>I've worked for principals who are really good at hiring well qualified teachers. &nbsp;My current one always seems to hit the jackpot. &nbsp;Part of the success is that grade level teams are in on the interviews. &nbsp;There is great emphasis in my district for teachers to collaborate so it makes sense that a team would want a new member that will operate well within that team. &nbsp;We also have a number of school wide initiatives and it's important that any new staff members buy into them for them to be successful.</p>
<p>I also work in a district that has more applicants than positions. &nbsp;It happens to be the highest paying district in my state and when you have so many applicants, you can usually choose more qualified people. &nbsp;The county next to us has the opposite problem. &nbsp;They have a teacher shortage and have had to import them from the Philippines.</p>
<p>In my 38 years, I can honestly say that I've worked with 3 people that should not be in the classroom. &nbsp;One was a middle aged person who was a new teacher. &nbsp;Our principal got her out within the first year. &nbsp;Another was a burn out who retired. &nbsp;The third was a special ed teacher with about 15 years experience who left our school. &nbsp;I have no idea what became of her. &nbsp;The worst teacher my kids had was 9th grade English teacher with 3 years experience who quit at the end of the year. &nbsp;The best one was their 9th grade social studies teacher who had 25 years experience and who had been a student at the same school. &nbsp;Some kids though he was "mean" but he consistently held high expectations and he was the only high school teacher that ever called us with any concerns.</p>
<p>I've worked with teachers that I thought were "crotchety" but they got the job done. &nbsp;While I would prefer that kids all have nurturing teachers, they do have to learn to get along with all types of personalities. &nbsp;If the teacher is ultimately a decent teacher, "grouchiness" shouldn't necessarily matter--certainly not to the testing fanatics.</p>
<p>Principals can control who works at their school whether the teachers are union or not.</p>

  </div>
