  <div class="ct">
  
<p>Though we had a few youngsters with disabilities in my elementary classrooms (late 1950s-early 1960s in Huntsville AL), we mainstreamed them manually. &nbsp;Two or three of us were asked (and not averse) to be stewards of an individual, for extensive tutorials in reading and arithmetic. &nbsp;We seemed to be working together for group success, back in those days. &nbsp;That may be selective memory, of course. &nbsp;Most of my learning took place at home, out of books, and from my under-educated but highly intelligent parents.</p>
<p>Our city schools weren't integrated until my senior year of high school ('68-'69), and there were few Hispanics noticed in our region at the time. &nbsp;Of course, the teachers themselves were a highly diverse group, often spouses of engineers hired by NASA from all over the world.</p>
<p>But you are absolutely right: &nbsp;what we call 'universal public education' has never really lived up to the name, and its quality has been spotty at best -- unless your family was wealthy.</p>

