<li id="c253">
  <div class="cx" id="cx51229039">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">True; Continuity is a Correlate of Success</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1234916/51229039#c253?mode=alone;showrate=1#c253">3+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:306236">musiclady</a>, <a href="/user/uid:972826">jsb16</a>, <a href="/user/uid:15174">elfling</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>I teach in my high school's "Occupational Course of Study" (for students with mild to moderate disabilities), as well as the College-Track Course of Study. The OCS program is small, and it requires the teacher to have certification in both High School English and Exceptional Children, and I'm the only faculty member who has both, so I teacher all four grades. I see the same kids each year: Sophomores to Juniors to Seniors. We all don't always get along perfectly well, because we're all very different people, but over the years we've built relationships.</p>
<p>Little things make a difference: My students still get irritated when I call them on disruptive behavior, and I still get irritated when they make smart-ass comments or refuse to do an assignment. But we all kind of know how to handle each other.</p>
<p>I also know them well enough to help new teachers who have these students in their own classes. For example, when students are corrected, if they mouth off or talk back, school rules say they get sent to the office. But one of my students has anger management issues, and copes with frustration by carrying on about how he wasn't doing whatever I said he was doing and it's totally unfair and stupid and he hates school and I'm just picking on him and so on. But he does it in a "clearly audible muttering" way; and it helps him "save face" while going ahead and doing what he's been asked to do. Because I know this about him, I have developed selective deafness in his case; and I can share this information with a teacher who hasn't taught him before. Everybody wins.</p>
<p>I am not any sort of super-teacher; all of our students will go to their previous years' teachers for advice or to blow off steam. When you get a whole new slew of teachers each year, kids lose that connection, and their education suffers.</p>
<p>Okay, I've ranted enough. Apologies for my vehemence, and for any rudeness I've directed at anyone. Thanks for writing this.</p>

  </div>
