<li id="c179">
  <div class="cx" id="cx51227443">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">To 0112358 and others who make assumptions about </span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1234916/51227443#c179?mode=alone;showrate=1#c179">9+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:10302">Caniac41</a>, <a href="/user/uid:17483">ssgbryan</a>, <a href="/user/uid:15174">elfling</a>, <a href="/user/uid:129942">rodentrancher</a>, <a href="/user/uid:71416">Naniboujou</a>, <a href="/user/uid:36118">RuralLiberal</a>, <a href="/user/uid:972826">jsb16</a>, <a href="/user/uid:120115">Calamity Jean</a>, <a href="/user/uid:62286">JanL</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>the demands of teachers' jobs:</p>
<p>1.) I work 60 hours a week, 6 days a week, all school year. No time for a life. I teach over 150 students, and respond to their parents' emails and meet with them after school regularly, as well as writing plans and grading papers.<br />
2.) I am not paid in the summer. I have to put money away all year to have enough to pay bills in summer. No money for vacation. Most teachers get summer jobs because they can't make the money stretch all year. Where do you live that teachers have such high pay?<br />
3.) The state requires continuing education to keep a teaching license. This comes out of teachers' pockets or is added to their debt. Most states require a Master's degree; have you priced them lately?<br />
4.) With my income, I couldn't afford rent or mortgage for even a tiny house without my spouse's help.</p>

  </div>
