<li id="c298">
  <div class="cx" id="cx51231884">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">Yes.</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1234916/51231884#c298?mode=alone;showrate=1#c298">2+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:15174">elfling</a>, <a href="/user/uid:273307">pdxteacher</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>I teach in the DC Suburbs. &nbsp;Our younger and single teachers all have second jobs. &nbsp;Most of them tutor at night and on weekends. &nbsp;They also are the first ones to sign up to teach summer school. &nbsp;Our "official" school hours are 8:15 to 3:45. &nbsp;I get to school between 7:45 and 8 am and the parking lot is already full. &nbsp;It's also full when I leave at 5, bringing home a bookbag with more work in it.</p>
<p>The problem is that they keep adding things to our plate without taking anything away. &nbsp;This year, I find out that our arts team (I'm the music teacher) is expected to post weekly notes for all of the grade level teachers and send home a monthly newsletter to our 700 + students. &nbsp; That amounts to more work in addition to the new curriculum that we are implementing. &nbsp;I also lost 90 minutes of planning time per week due to an increase in enrollment so I have more students and less time in which to grade them. &nbsp;This will mean more work at home. &nbsp;I typically spend Sunday doing school work.</p>
<p>I'm not complaining. &nbsp;I'm just saying that this is how it is. &nbsp;Most of us understood that going in. &nbsp;It just gets really frustrating to hear people say--"you only work 9 - 3 &nbsp;nine months a year and get all that vacation time" which simply isn't true.</p>
<p>Back in the 90's our state teachers association did a survey and found that the average teacher in our state worked 55 hours a week. &nbsp;I'd say that the number of hours have increased.</p>

