<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1234916/51225849#c48?mode=alone;showrate=1#c48">16+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:62286">JanL</a>, <a href="/user/uid:199259">worldlotus</a>, <a href="/user/uid:36118">RuralLiberal</a>, <a href="/user/uid:111341">AnnieJo</a>, <a href="/user/uid:56610">ladybug53</a>, <a href="/user/uid:129942">rodentrancher</a>, <a href="/user/uid:257122">belinda ridgewood</a>, <a href="/user/uid:15174">elfling</a>, <a href="/user/uid:233649">Mostel26</a>, <a href="/user/uid:27914">antirove</a>, <a href="/user/uid:306236">musiclady</a>, <a href="/user/uid:217457">Laurel in CA</a>, <a href="/user/uid:273307">pdxteacher</a>, <a href="/user/uid:302836">AverageJoe42</a>, <a href="/user/uid:235498">TRsCousin</a>, <a href="/user/uid:972826">jsb16</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>is not at all with how it conceives education nor the standards it proposes that students should be held to. &nbsp;No, the problem is that most states are still in the early to middle stages of implementing the previous set of standards and frameworks, and now they have to throw out all of the work they've done developing their standards and training teachers to use them in order to implement the entirely new set of standards that have come down from the federal department of education.</p>
<p>The Common Core represents a body of knowledge that teachers are expected to train their students to use and understand. &nbsp;The Core is similar to though different from the existing state standards, and it does in fact take time and training to get teachers up to speed on what those differences are and what expectations will now be used to evaluate their performance. &nbsp;It is a big change, and it is the second or third such big change to come down the pike in the last twenty years.</p>
<p>Bad evaluations can lead to firing. &nbsp;Before you judge that teacher too harshly, think for two seconds about the kinds of external pressures her school district is subjecting her to.</p>
<p>Teaching is already a difficult job. &nbsp;Changing the rules of the game every five years makes it indescribably so.</p>

