  <div class="ct">
  
<p>Are there large numbers of kids who have learned and mastered the material, yet fail the tests? I don't think so.</p>
<p>The anti-testing argument is similar to fable of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Emperor%27s_New_Clothes">The Emperor's New Clothes.</a> We ask kids to solve math problems and they cannot. We ask them to read and they cannot. We ask them questions about History, Geography, and Science, and they cannot answer.</p>
<p>Yet, we are told by the Entrenched Educational Establishment that this is not failure! Instead there are mystical, invisible skills that these kids are acquiring -- that our tests can't measure.</p>
<p>These unmeasurable skills seem to only be visible to those with a direct interest in the entrenched <em>status quo</em>.</p>
<p>Tests are imperfect and it isn't fair to blame teachers for 100% of their kids' progress. Most blame belongs with the parents, community, and socioeconomic system. But I am highly skeptical of any who say that kids are making "progress" when those kids keep flunking tests.</p>
<p>If kids fail tests, we must assume they didn't learn. The burden of proof is on those who would say otherwise.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
