   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">I just want to remind you</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1234916/51225954#c62?mode=alone;showrate=1#c62">22+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:3624">decisivemoment</a>, <a href="/user/uid:199259">worldlotus</a>, <a href="/user/uid:36118">RuralLiberal</a>, <a href="/user/uid:100966">Aunt Martha</a>, <a href="/user/uid:71416">Naniboujou</a>, <a href="/user/uid:56610">ladybug53</a>, <a href="/user/uid:219706">judyms9</a>, <a href="/user/uid:15174">elfling</a>, <a href="/user/uid:257122">belinda ridgewood</a>, <a href="/user/uid:64007">CarolinW</a>, <a href="/user/uid:107006">AuntieM</a>, <a href="/user/uid:233649">Mostel26</a>, <a href="/user/uid:197476">midnight lurker</a>, <a href="/user/uid:27914">antirove</a>, <a href="/user/uid:107036">dizzydean</a>, <a href="/user/uid:99191">RosyFinch</a>, <a href="/user/uid:71628">fiddler crabby</a>, <a href="/user/uid:956537">allison88</a>, <a href="/user/uid:273307">pdxteacher</a>, <a href="/user/uid:154707">Dragon5616</a>, <a href="/user/uid:302836">AverageJoe42</a>, <a href="/user/uid:235498">TRsCousin</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>that what you so glibly refer to as the "Entrenched Educational Establishment" is in large part composed of organized labor, teachers unions that have fought hard over the years to get a small degree of professional dignity for an exploited and abused workforce.</p>
<p>Back in the day, before unions, teachers were graded on their handwriting, on the length of their skirts, on the cleanliness of their classrooms. &nbsp;They were fired for dating, much less getting married or pregnant.</p>
<p>Teachers have won job security and a pay scale based on seniority and educational attainment. &nbsp;They can be, and frequently are, fired for cause, but administrators cannot fire a professional status teacher on a whim.</p>
<p>When I worked at a charter school, the principal made up the salaries on the fly. &nbsp;The fact I held a Ph.D. in the subject I taught, and that I had thirteen years teaching it at the college level, was irrelevant; he simply picked a number out of the air and told me that was how much I would get paid. &nbsp;The benefits at that school were a joke -- we used the health plan my wife was offered at her private school, because it was cheaper and covered better.</p>
<p>Ed reform in the US today, while couched in the language of improving outcomes for kids, is really about breaking unions. &nbsp;In the real world, teachers unions are at the forefront of searching for ways to improve our craft.</p>

