  <a href="/user/uid:217457">Laurel in CA</a>, <a href="/user/uid:273307">pdxteacher</a>, <a href="/user/uid:107036">dizzydean</a>, <a href="/user/uid:10302">Caniac41</a>, <a href="/user/uid:71416">Naniboujou</a>, <a href="/user/uid:205618">cailloux</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>Back in the late 90's, our district addressed the disparity between rich and poor schools. &nbsp;I teach in the DC suburbs in the largest district in MD--200 schools. &nbsp;We have some extremely wealthy areas in our county--multimillion dollar homes. &nbsp;Then we have areas like the one I teach in: &nbsp;95% very diverse minority, 70% poverty rate and largely non English speaking. &nbsp;Schools like mine have smaller class sizes and more resources than those in wealthy areas. &nbsp;Back in the 90's it was determined that getting kids on grade level when they were young would benefit them, so all day kindergarten was put in place and class size caps of 15 for grades K - 2. &nbsp;Extra reading and math support teachers, special ed. resource and ESOL teachers were added. &nbsp;Free summer programs were also added. &nbsp;The effort paid off. &nbsp;</p>
<p>The problem is when an entire district is poor and there simply are no resources. &nbsp;I often wonder why some states don't move to larger school districts to help spread the resources to those who need them.</p>

  </div>
