<li id="c225">
  <div class="cx" id="cx51228258">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">It's not always possible to make your district</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1234916/51228258#c225?mode=alone;showrate=1#c225">4+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:71416">Naniboujou</a>, <a href="/user/uid:205618">cailloux</a>, <a href="/user/uid:972826">jsb16</a>, <a href="/user/uid:201252">Be Skeptical</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>large enough to get high income neighborhoods. There are some very large districts in California that are 80%+ free and reduced lunch (FRL). This is the reality, in a world where more than half the kids in the nation qualify for FRL and a quarter live below the poverty line.</p>
<p>But there's also no reason schools have to be funded solely by local property taxes, and I would argue that it's terrible practice to do so.</p>
<p>In California, very wealthy areas are funded almost only by property taxes. Those are perversely called "Basic Aid" districts because they only get a tiny amount from the state. However, all districts are entitled to a floor amount of funding per student, and the state pays the difference between property tax receipts and that amount on a per daily attendance basis.</p>
<p>To give you a sense of how important that is, for our school, the property taxes only raise $800,000, but the budget is nearly $3 million.</p>
<p>It's also the case that a student's ADA money follows them - so there's no financial problem for a student to come in to our district if we have space.</p>
<p>California is about to try a big experiment, called the Local Control Funding Formula, basically wrapping all the state money into a per student number, giving disadvantaged students a bonus, and then sending that to districts without so many restrictions on how the money can be spent. It will be interesting to see how this works out.</p>
<p>(My biggest concern with LCFF is whether the base grant is high enough to meet the needs of non-disadvantaged students.)</p>

