  <div class="ct">
  
<p>mainly on performance based tests--individual performances--whether they be singing skills, reading notation and playing it on an instrument etc. &nbsp;There are a few skills done on paper, but the majority are not. &nbsp;A written standardized test in elementary music will mean that I can no longer emphasize the making of music. &nbsp;Students will be learning about music and not becoming active musicians. &nbsp;The simple fact is that standardized tests must be easy and quick to administer and grade which the authentic assessments that I give are not.</p>
<p>Another issue with state standardized testing for content area like mine is that there is little consistency from district to district. &nbsp;My students have music once a week for 45 - 50 minutes. &nbsp;The students in the district where I live, however, have music 2 - 3 times a week for 90 minutes a week. &nbsp;It would be ludicrous for students in both districts to take the same test.</p>
<p>My district refused Race to the Top money so our evaluations will measure student achievement differently than those who would base an evaluation on test scores.</p>

