  <div class="ct">
  
<p>to attend a private school. &nbsp;Many of the big networks of charter schools are for-profit institutions, and even those that are non-profit still compete with public schools for those tax dollars.</p>
<p>Public education in the United States has a long history, dating well before the Civil War. &nbsp;Its ethos is to provide free quality education to every student who walks in the door, financed through modest taxes on the entire community. &nbsp;It is eminently social from top to bottom.</p>
<p>Private education selects its students (in charters, they do this through a lottery, but many voucher schools simply choose among applicants), and the tuition charged to those individuals goes to profit the teachers and owners of the institution. &nbsp;It is eminently a private activity.</p>
<p>Me, I believe in government. &nbsp;That is, I believe government acting on its own can be a positive force for social good. &nbsp;I see no need to charge property taxes to the elderly and the childless and pass that money on to private companies, the owners of which might very well use their profits to purchase themselves yachts and vacation homes in the Caribbean.</p>
<p>The public sector may not always deliver on its promise of quality education for all, but it tries. &nbsp;Private schools, especially for-profit private schools, promise investors a return. &nbsp;Education be damned.</p>

