<li id="c91">
  <div class="cx" id="cx51226218">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">Making the voucher large is all very well, but</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1234916/51226218#c91?mode=alone;showrate=1#c91">3+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:233649">Mostel26</a>, <a href="/user/uid:71416">Naniboujou</a>, <a href="/user/uid:10302">Caniac41</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>explain to me, how, exactly, this will happen politically.</p>
<p>The political dynamic behind almost every voucher scheme I've seen is either a) saving money in general or b) spending less on public education. &nbsp;The motivation behind vouchers overwhelmingly isn't reform, it's to spend less. &nbsp;In other words, make the voucher small. &nbsp;At the very least, smaller than what we're now spending in general education levy/state aid/other per student. &nbsp;Quality control doesn't enter into the picture except for lip service. &nbsp;And so, vouchers end up being tagged as morally defective because they're a vehicle for morally defective behavior.</p>
<p>Unless you can strip that motivation out, vouchers will simply undermine a service like K-12 education. &nbsp;And, in the one part of the educational sector where voucher-style finance has been even minimally successful, higher education, providers have returned the favor with runaway costs. &nbsp;</p>
<p>But nobody seems to have the balls or the competence to actually try to reform existing institutions. &nbsp;One example is size; moderate school districts do way better than small ones that can't provide the necessary range of services or large ones that are topheavy and unresponsive to change. &nbsp;You know, like consolidate rural districts that are too small, or divide big city school districts that are too big. &nbsp;It's difficult, because it involves challenging politicians and administrators who want to keep things they way they are. &nbsp;But guess what, it actually does something for the people who count, the kids, and the teachers who teach them. &nbsp;And yet we tiptoe around the edges of rural consolidation and completely avoid big city division.</p>
<p>In the end, the political formula for success in the biggest variety of situations is broadening the stakeholder base and making a community service out of things. &nbsp;You know, like a typical well-run moderate-size K-12 school district that's treated as a community asset, not just a glorified day-care center.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:3624">decisivemoment</a> on <a href="/comments/1234916/51226218#c91">Sun Sep 01, 2013 at 11:11:53 AM PDT</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  [ <a href="#c59">Parent</a> ] 
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	


