  <div class="ct">
  
<p>...if we sell the Teachers' Unions on it.</p>
<p>We make a deal:</p>
<blockquote>-- We agree to pump <strong>serious</strong> funding increases into the system in the form of Charters/Vouchers/Merit-Pay. The <em>total cash pie</em> gets bigger.
<p>&nbsp;-- In return, the Unions must agree to allow more of (not all) the pie to be <em>sliced</em> based on performance/tests/parental-school-choice.</p>
</blockquote>
That is the basic idea. There will need to be much haggling over particulars.
<p>Remember, Charters are not necessarily anti-union. Here in NYC, the UFT actually runs some Charter Schools. Who is better qualified to design a school than a group of pro teachers? What parent, given the choice, would not pick a teacher-run Charter over a Corporate-run one?</p>
<p>But right now the Right-Wing is controlling the reform narrative. They are changing how the pie is sliced <strong><em>without making it bigger</em></strong>. And they are successful because inner-city families (like mine) who are Natural Democrats are willing to sell out the Unions if it helps our kids.</p>
<p><em>We will do anything if it helps our kids. <strong>Anything</strong>.</em></p>
<p>Reform is coming. We can do it <strong>our</strong> way or let the Koch Brothers do it <strong>their</strong> way. But reform is coming.</p>

