    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>in poor neighborhoods may not have an incentive to remove bad teachers is because they don't think they can get better applicants.</p>
<p>That's a real problem. Some really terrible schools are not nice places to be, not for kids, not for adults either. A school with high turnover is IME a red flag that there may be a problem there, with the facilities, with the administration, or with the community.</p>
<p>If a principal is really inflicting terrible teachers on students because he doesn't care, he needs to be removed. Simple as that.</p>
<p>All schools need to be clean. All schools need to be safe. And teachers like to work with kids and families who are excited about learning. Teachers like to work with principals that solve their problems and that value them as professionals.</p>
<p>Schools in really poor neighborhoods need a lot more resources to do what schools in wealthier communities take for granted. They probably need smaller student to staff ratios. They probably need more money for facilities and field trips. We don't fund low income schools to the same level that high income areas are funded, especially not when you consider fundraising by PTAs and the value of volunteer time. Our school funding mechanisms aren't equitable, not at all.</p>

