<li id="c23">
  <div class="cx" id="cx51225651">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">two things</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1234916/51225651#c23?mode=alone;showrate=1#c23">5+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:71416">Naniboujou</a>, <a href="/user/uid:233649">Mostel26</a>, <a href="/user/uid:99191">RosyFinch</a>, <a href="/user/uid:31133">ManhattanMan</a>, <a href="/user/uid:76458">Unitary Moonbat</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>There are two things going on here. &nbsp;First over the past 50 years or so we have gotten very good at educating everyone, and opening up opportunity for everyone. &nbsp;For example, Instead of 15 students in calculus at a few selects schools, we have 40 or more students in calculus at every school. &nbsp;In Houston, for example, arguable the best most competitive school in the city is 10% white, 30% Hispanic, 25% African american and 40% Asian, with 50% on free or reduced lunch(under represent white, over represent asian). &nbsp;That is diversity, that is educating the population of Houston no matter who they are.</p>
<p>And it scares the crap out of so many people because it means that if you are not competitive, if you are just looking for your kid to get the education that you got just because you were entitled, it is not going to happen. &nbsp;So we have charter schools opening up everywhere diverting money from those who want an education from those who are willing to work for it. &nbsp;Years ago I had an argument with a coworker over education in they city. &nbsp;She claimed that her kids could not get a good education. Finally she admitted that they were not willing to work in primary school, so they could not test into a good school, so she moved to the suburbs where the competition was not so great.</p>
<p>Second is teachers. I am not going to say anything about TFA teachers &nbsp;They are dedicated to the students and work hard, and most have content knowledge though some do not. &nbsp;However, content knowledge is not everything. &nbsp;I know older teachers who are not so great at content knowledge but are expert at getting students to learn and integrate knowledge. &nbsp;This is really the only skill that matters. &nbsp;Student learning. &nbsp;And not just learning what is in the curriculum, but learning how to live and how to get along. &nbsp;And if the only people you have teaching are those who made 4.0 averages from the top schools, where is the diversity in that? &nbsp;school is not about getting a 4.0, it is about learning, and experiencing, and sometimes failing. &nbsp;TFA picks to form a &nbsp;very homogeneous corp, where everyone has the same perspective on what it means to succeed. &nbsp;It is an echo chamber that lacks alternative voices</p>
<p>And this is what is common between the new teachers and new schools that are the new reform. &nbsp;Consistency that is controlled from top. &nbsp;Where once a teacher could teach what the teacher loved, in a way that would enliven it to the students, now a teacher covers what is on the test, in a way that is consistent with what outside evaluators consider good practices. &nbsp;This is nothing more than a paycheck and paying off student debts. &nbsp;There is nothing for the students in reform.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:237660">lowt</a> on <a href="/comments/1234916/51225651#c23">Sun Sep 01, 2013 at 10:12:01 AM PDT</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	





