<p>"Calcification and resentment" among senior teachers, the first question we should be asking ourselves is why we would administer our schools so poorly that our employees apparently hate their jobs.</p>
<p>I am lucky to see amazing, enthusiastic, capable teachers with a range of experience. My sense is that the best arrangement for a school is to have a mix of expert veterans and younger teachers. Everyone learns from everyone in this scenario: the younger teachers are mentored by the older; the older teachers are introduced to ideas that come from meeting and working with the new teachers. A great teacher is always learning from one's students, both the younger and the adult students.</p>
<p>The older teachers create stability in the school and the community; they know the kids and the families; they know what activities and resources are around. They have institutional memory of what has worked and what has not.</p>
