  <div class="ct">
  
<p>just like in any other profession.</p>
<p>It's important to remind folks that progressive reformers are asking for the following:</p>
<p>1) Give school site teams the ability to to hire the best licensed teachers for their students, regardless of seniority. Sometimes the best teachers are seasoned veterans. Sometimes they're newer to the profession. Let site teams make this decision.</p>
<p>2) Get site teams the ability to get rid of ineffective teachers. In Minnesota, a recent study asked teachers what percentage of their colleagues in their building shouldn't be in the classroom. The answer was between &nbsp;15-18 percent. &nbsp;In my particular district, less than one percent of tenured teachers are ever fired for poor teaching. This is nuts.</p>
<p>You can talk all about evil corporate privatizers....it's a great way of changing the subject from the actual policies being proposed. Heck, if I was trying defend the status quo, I'd change the subject too.</p>
<p>Because if the status quo was working, none of this would matter. Keep seniority. Let teachers keep their jobs for life regardless of performance. But in Minneapolis, less than 50 percent of our children of color are doing math and reading at grade level; less than 40 percent graduate from high school on-time.</p>
<p>Yes, poverty plays a role. Yes, we need to support income equality, better health-care, etc. But it's not &nbsp;an either-or choice. We must do these things AND start design our schools around the success of our actual students as opposed to the comfort and convenience of adults.</p>
<p>Because if less than 50 percent of white kids were reading at grade level, if less than 40 percent were graduating on time, <strong>we would have already changed our schools to work better for these kids.</strong> We would have changed the staff, the school day, school year, curriculum, whatever if took because it white kids were failing, it would be a big-time crisis.<br /></p>

