</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>and we will always want them to be better. Let's just stipulate that up front.</p>
<p>We are not doing well enough by our low income and minority kids. Totally true. That said, we are also doing better by them than we ever have. There is no "Golden Age" when it was better to be a youngster of color in the American education than it is today.</p>
<p>Your "poverty plays a role" though I think is dismissive. ~25% of American kids live in poverty. That's a shamefully low standard for any child, let alone a quarter of our kids. Most of these kids are damaged by that experience - they lack a safe, quiet place to be; they lack security for themselves or their possessions; they lack adequate medical and dental care. Poverty is neurologically damaging and some of these kids have PTSD. Giving them two math classes a day and demanding they study harder is probably not a solution.</p>
<p>Attendance plays a role. Many low income kids, for whatever reason, also have very poor attendance. The teachers can't teach the kids who don't come to school.</p>
<p>A lot of these kids are already behind when they show up for Kindergarten. These kids and families need more support from programs like Head Start and state preschool programs, not less.</p>
<p>Peers are important. Being surrounded by peers who are high achieving and expected to be high achieving is probably more important than the teachers you have. When we have districts that are 80%+ free and reduced lunch, you're not going to be able to make classrooms with this advantage. And so, you need more resources to build this culture for these kids. In most places in the US, low income districts and schools like this also have less money to spend, and fewer volunteers to work with kids.</p>

  </div>
