    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>Great diary. &nbsp;There are several aspects that technology adds to this dynamic:</p>
<p>1. This is the further McDonadlization of education, in this case highlighting the acceptability of turnover, as the job becomes "McDonadlized" through standardization and quantification.</p>
<p>2. &nbsp;Technology will give us the next step--turning teachers into facilitators in a "student-centric" environment, but where the students "explore content" that is provided on-line or through computerized educational models developed by the textbook companies. &nbsp;Teachers no longer "teach" in the "flipped classroom" but merely assist students to enhance their learning experience. &nbsp;In this model (already showing up in charter schools), young facilitators--paid less than teachers, naturally--are required to be "people persons" with good computer and internet skills. &nbsp;No content knowledge required.</p>
<p>3. &nbsp;Finally the technology gap between the older and younger teachers makes itself manifest in performance ratings. &nbsp;In my own school, several sections of the performance review are based on the integration of technology in the classroom, so that students can ?master 21st century skills". &nbsp;Never mind that the class observed was an actual discussion about ethics and morals. &nbsp;In the administrator's mind, some part of the daily classroom experience must involve students staring at screens, regardless of the effectiveness of that method....</p>

  </div>
