<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1234916/51227822#c200?mode=alone;showrate=1#c200">0+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>her "flipped classroom" this summer. &nbsp;She actually plans to have kids watch how-to videos as homework the night before, &nbsp;then have them "practice" in the classroom! My mouth fell open when she explained that she would be "teaching" math this way. She thinks she's being modern and making use of technology. Sad.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:273307">pdxteacher</a> on <a href="/comments/1234916/51227822#c200">Sun Sep 01, 2013 at 02:43:59 PM PDT</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  [ <a href="#c44">Parent</a> ] 
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	


	<ul id="k51227822" class="cm i1">




<li id="c241">
  <div class="cx" id="cx51228555">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">This is IMHO a really promising idea</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1234916/51228555#c241?mode=alone;showrate=1#c241">0+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>the idea of making the videos the homework and then bringing the homework into the classroom. The advantage is that you've gotten the concept of the material out there, and then you can spend class time on the difficult areas and on working with the kids on the problems, instead of on lecturing.</p>
<p>You can get your best lecture recorded, and you can integrate it with other video or animated materials, if you're really awesome. Kids who are out sick can still get the lecture.</p>
<p>It means that you don't need to have expert parents at home to help you with homework, too.</p>
<p>However, this only works if you can count on all the kids to watch the videos. Can you? I don't know.</p>
<p>And of course, there's the matter of the technology. If the video requires an internet connection, not everyone has one. Can you count on kids being able to take tablets home and be able to keep them safe? Can you count on them being able to sit and watch/listen in an uninterrupted spot for the requisite time?</p>
<p>As an educational idea, I really like it. As a practical idea, I know that right now it will not work in our district.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig">
<i>Fry, don't be a hero! It's not covered by our health plan!</i>
</p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:15174">elfling</a> on <a href="/comments/1234916/51228555#c241">Sun Sep 01, 2013 at 04:10:27 PM PDT</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  [ <a href="#c200">Parent</a> ] 
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	


	<ul id="k51228555" class="cm i1">




<li id="c247">
  <div class="cx" id="cx51228749">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">I wish I agreed</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1234916/51228749#c247?mode=alone;showrate=1#c247">0+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>I respect your point of view, but replacing the interaction and dynamic, multi-layered discussion that takes place in the classroom with a how-to video is like replacing Thanksgiving with a TV dinner. &nbsp;As a math teacher, I see it as a poor idea. I do, however, appreciate having Khan Academy videos available as a back-up resource for students who have been absent.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:273307">pdxteacher</a> on <a href="/comments/1234916/51228749#c247">Sun Sep 01, 2013 at 04:40:54 PM PDT</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  [ <a href="#c241">Parent</a> ] 
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	


	<ul id="k51228749" class="cm i1">




<li id="c265">
  <div class="cx" id="cx51229646">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">Well, I see it the other way</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1234916/51229646#c265?mode=alone;showrate=1#c265">0+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>You get the basic out there, you get everyone's minds primed with the ideas for the lesson, and <strong>then</strong> you can jump right into discussion and practice. It should yield more time for the human to human interaction, with more student classroom time being active participation instead of passive listening.</p>
<p>That's the theory.</p>
<p>I think as a practical matter, though, this falls into dust if the kids don't do the video homework, and in most places the logistics of life are not necessarily making this possible. Our community does not generally have internet. Lots of kids do their homework now on the bus, or at the sidelines at practice, or in a car. All these things are real problems in terms of deploying it this year.</p>
<p>I would love to hear what your friend's experiences are of it in practice.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig">
<i>Fry, don't be a hero! It's not covered by our health plan!</i>
</p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:15174">elfling</a> on <a href="/comments/1234916/51229646#c265">Sun Sep 01, 2013 at 06:46:14 PM PDT</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  [ <a href="#c247">Parent</a> ] 
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	


	<ul id="k51229646" class="cm i1">




<li id="c266">
  <div class="cx" id="cx51229905">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">I can tell you what my classroom is like</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1234916/51229905#c266?mode=alone;showrate=1#c266">1+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:15174">elfling</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>Teaching and learning is a complex, multi-layered experience. &nbsp;I teach using something between magician and Socrates- I pose questions, challenge assumptions, have kids come up front and explain their strategies. &nbsp;To hand all of that excitement over to a flat, static video, where the student is a passive observer, is to turn my back on all that I've learned that education can be. &nbsp;Think of all of the varying levels of students' abilities, learning styles, intelligences- how much better a real, live experience can be than a video.</p>
<p>Going this route is to relegate teaching to technicians. &nbsp;Sit down, children, and watch this.</p>
<p>Saying that having them watch a video primes them so that they can follow up in class- well, that would be, for me, like telling them all about how the rabbit was pulled out of the hat first, then having them come in to watch the show. &nbsp;Borrring! Depresses me to think of giving up the excitement for that!</p>
<p>In my class, students learn to have fun and ponder the infinite with math. &nbsp;Not just to master technical skills.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:273307">pdxteacher</a> on <a href="/comments/1234916/51229905#c266">Sun Sep 01, 2013 at 07:20:52 PM PDT</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  [ <a href="#c265">Parent</a> ] 
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	


	<ul id="k51229905" class="cm i1">




<li id="c274">
  <div class="cx" id="cx51230604">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">The video doesn't have to be static :-)</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1234916/51230604#c274?mode=alone;showrate=1#c274">1+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:273307">pdxteacher</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>But I guess what I'm looking at is the other side of the coin, watching my daughter and her father spend an hour or so on a homework set, with him spending a lot of time actively tutoring her in the work. She gets home, she starts to work the problems, and elements that seemed obvious to her in class are suddenly not, especially not when she is tired and cranky.</p>
<p>My husband and I are both proficient in math well beyond calculus. Assisting her with algebra is well within our skillset.</p>
<p>However, I believe we are the only family in her class where this is so. It will only get worse as the kids get older.</p>
<p>I worry about the other kids who go home and have to struggle through homework alone.</p>
<p>Our school does try to go above and beyond, providing a 7th period that can be used for homework, and providing an academic assistance time three days a week after school.</p>
<p>I am glad what you are doing is working for your kids, and I love great math teachers who love the language of math. :-)</p>

  </div>
