<li id="c76">
  <div class="cx" id="cx51226089">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">Let me toss a little blame the other way</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1234916/51226089#c76?mode=alone;showrate=1#c76">7+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:107006">AuntieM</a>, <a href="/user/uid:15174">elfling</a>, <a href="/user/uid:117053">FG</a>, <a href="/user/uid:66587">Orinoco</a>, <a href="/user/uid:27914">antirove</a>, <a href="/user/uid:99191">RosyFinch</a>, <a href="/user/uid:141510">Willinois</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>First let me say that any notion that LACK of experience is a good thing is completely insane. &nbsp;Its not something anyone looks for in a cook, home builder, doctor, lawyer, photographer, actor or starting quarterback. &nbsp;Why in the world would teachers be different?</p>
<p>Now let me tell you about some of the attitudes from the teaching profession about what constitutes "experience."</p>
<p>I started teaching as a young Sergeant because in the Army that is what young Sergeants do. &nbsp;A basic function of an NCO is to teach others. &nbsp;Initially I was given VERY simple classes with little deviation from the Program of Instruction (POI). &nbsp;Before I could give the class to "students" I had to give it multiple times to NCOs senior to me - all of whom could give the class in their sleep. &nbsp;And when I gave the class one of them would be in the audience to grade me, correct any mistakes and help me get better for the next time. &nbsp;</p>
<p>As I moved up the experience ladder I progressed to longer, more detailed classes and was allowed to deviate from the POI more and more. &nbsp;Eventually I was one of the ones sitting in the practice classes helping someone more junior prepare for his first class. &nbsp;</p>
<p>While not exactly Socratic most classes had heavy interaction with the "students" because they tended to be hands on at some point. &nbsp;The Army stresses "Be, Know, Do" with its leaders - Be is having been trained in the task yourself, Know is knowing the task in depth, Do is doing the task successfully and repeatedly. &nbsp;It is rare that a class in the Army is given by someone who isnt an expert in that task. &nbsp;Preparation is stressed beyond what most could imagine. &nbsp;Every class has "Tasks, Conditions and Standards" that must be met. &nbsp;There are volumes of training aids that can, should or must be used for every class. &nbsp;We do rehearsals that would make Steve Jobs proud. &nbsp;</p>
<p>None of this should be foreign to any teacher. &nbsp;Anyone who is part of the teaching profession should recognize the process and implementation of that process. &nbsp;It is be easy to see that the Army teaches it people how to teach. &nbsp;And you would think that if something was that obvious it would be easy to quantify and qualify the level of experience in equivalent terms. &nbsp;You would think. &nbsp;But in fact that is the exact opposite of what happens in the real world.</p>
<p>Experienced soldiers who have taught thousands of hours of formal classes, written thousands of POIs, trained hundreds of others to teach are told "you dont have a teaching degree, no job." &nbsp;Soldiers with multiple degrees in other areas in addition to years, even decades of actual teaching experience are told that they cant be hired while someone with nothing other than a degree in education can. &nbsp;</p>
<p>For as long as I have had friends departing the military they have faced prejudice and obstacles to becoming teachers that few other professions do. &nbsp;Logistics companies value what Army logisticians bring. &nbsp;Intelligence officers have no issue finding people willing to pay for their experience. &nbsp;Yet very few districts make it easy for soldiers - most of who REALLY like teaching - to turn their experience into a job. &nbsp;</p>
<p>It is idiotic to think less experience is a good thing. &nbsp;But the teaching profession has said loud and clear that they only value &nbsp;experience on their terms. &nbsp;And that makes them look stupid, protectionist and calcified. &nbsp;</p>

  </div>
