  <a href="/user/uid:257122">belinda ridgewood</a>, <a href="/user/uid:56610">ladybug53</a>, <a href="/user/uid:71416">Naniboujou</a>, <a href="/user/uid:27914">antirove</a>, <a href="/user/uid:273307">pdxteacher</a>, <a href="/user/uid:15174">elfling</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>I speak of the Adult Ed Division of the Los Angeles Unified School District. After years of incremental cut-backs and downsizing of course offerings, the biggest collapse came in 2012. There were hundreds of layoffs, mandatory transfers and curriculum changes.</p>
<p>One criteria to be applied was Longevity - the Adult Ed equivalent of Seniority. It came as a shock to many veteran teachers that their decades of teaching magically were reset to zero, or maybe 1-2 years. Without the benefit of Longevity, many lost their jobs when their hourly wage was highest. And, they lost health coverage when replacement coverage would be most pricey - if available at all. &nbsp;</p>
<p>How did this happen? Legally. With union representation too.</p>
<p>Contract renegotiation in early 2000's (using volunteer negotiators not a labor attorney) altered the formula for Longevity to elow the existing formula. Subsequently, when hours were reduced or summer sessions omitted, lots of teachers got their Longevity reset to zero. That meant layoffs. BTW: Tenure processing had been On Hold for years - or arbitrarily denied to very qualified older teachers.</p>
<p>Did teachers know all this when they ratified the contract? I don't know, I wasn't there at the time. Typically, only key points of a revised 420-page contract are handed out as bullet points on union vote day. But I suspect it would have passed.</p>
<p>Longevity reset (linked to the cost of health benefits) was considered minor to avoiding co-pays. And Adult Ed was in expansion mode at the time..layoffs seemed remote.</p>
<p>Side Point: This is yet another major, major selling point for Single Payer Healthcare - not linked to employment. But that will be another post.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>

