<li id="c319">
  <div class="cx" id="cx51272452">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">THANK YOU, THANK YOU, THANK YOU</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1234916/51272452#c319?mode=alone;showrate=1#c319">0+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>I am so sick of people, especially progressives, who devalue the labor of professional educators. &nbsp;I am sick of (some) young teachers who view their older colleagues in negative ways, dismiss their advice as if it has no value.</p>
<p>I am a veteran teacher, now retired, but still substituting occasionally. &nbsp;I started teaching in 1967 and retired in 2004. &nbsp;But since 2004, I did several long term sub positions, and now continue to sub but only short term.</p>
<p>I hear from students fairly regularly, especially since the internet. &nbsp;Their feedback has always been a way for me to look back and learn what impressed their memories about our time together. &nbsp;The strengths in subject areas I felt for myself were always math and social sciences. &nbsp; But my best asset, I believe, was giving my 6th grade <em>(mostly though a few years of 5th and a few as the media center/librarian/technology educator)</em> students a sense of belonging and trust, an enthusiasm and excitement for learning regardless of the subject. &nbsp; I shared my enthusiasm with them whether it was music or art or sports. &nbsp;They remember those things. &nbsp; Joie de vivre is a hallmark of a good learning environment. &nbsp; My early years were when 6th was in elementary school and so I got to teach all subjects and I LOVED IT. &nbsp; I did not have to be an expert in all those areas and often, I learned along side my students. &nbsp;When computers first came into the buildings, I was hooked. &nbsp; I started my MA in technology ed before I even owned a computer. &nbsp; As new computers would come into the building, I, along with my students, learned all about them, stumbling along the way, but learning. &nbsp;It was exciting. I felt it and more importantly my students did. But then, I was not instructed, forced, demanded to use my time more wisely, in drill and practice, for the purpose of higher scores on some test. &nbsp; We, as a society, have lost sight of the value given our children, when they are allowed to explore, to fail, to try again. &nbsp; We have allowed the corporations turn our teachers into the conduit for turning students into drones. &nbsp; Those veteran teachers fighting against the corporatization/privatization of public education are now systematically and publicly demonized.</p>
<p>So now, as I sub, <em>sometimes</em>, I see looks of disappointment from some teachers when they see my gray hair. &nbsp;At nearly 68 years, I am a "senior" teacher and few seniors, like the one mentioned in the diary, are left in most buildings. &nbsp;</p>
<p>In my time as a teacher, I was active in our union, was a building rep for many years. &nbsp;In the seventies, I found myself on strike twice <em>(two different districts as I had moved to a new state). &nbsp;</em>I fought passionately along side colleagues to keep the right of collective bargaining, to make sure teachers had a say so over working conditions. &nbsp; Neither time on strike was salary the issue. &nbsp;Class size, curriculum development, building safety, student safety, health benefits were always top on the list. &nbsp; I never went into education to get rich. &nbsp;No one I know did. &nbsp; But I did know that one of the benefits, besides doing what I loved, was security for health and retirement.</p>
<p>I have mentored young teachers, taught graduate classes for teachers working on masters' degrees at both public and private colleges. &nbsp;I have an MA in Educational Technology and a master's equivalent in counseling. &nbsp;When I was asked for years "what do you teach?" my answer was always "children". &nbsp; It is my belief that the best teachers are not subject centered but rather student centered. &nbsp; A good classroom has the right balance of "sage on the stage" and "guide on the side". &nbsp; That balance changes often depending on the class, the child, the subject matter. &nbsp; &nbsp;The best teachers' in my estimation are the ones whose students leave her/his class with a love of learning; with a thirst for knowledge; &nbsp;with a joyful curiosity about everything. &nbsp;</p>
<p>I was a good teacher when I started but I had so much to learn and often my students were my teachers. &nbsp; &nbsp;My unbridled enthusiasm helped me in the early years but experience made me a much better teacher decades later.</p>
<p>TFA scares me because it has gained such a foothold in the minds of the public. &nbsp;When inexperienced <em>(and in my opinion, less than mediocre)</em> educators like Michelle Rhee are given so much power and voice, we have lost our way. &nbsp;I am saddened about the lack of support from this president for public education; disgusted with Arne Duncan and his philosophy given such credence; and stunned at the progressive community's lack of support for public education.</p>
<p>I believe that turnover in staff at schools is not good, especially in poor communities. &nbsp;Consistency and trust are needed in schools but the lack of public support for public education is killing off those things. &nbsp; Experienced teachers can and do role model for younger teachers but younger teachers need to be open to the fact that experience does matter.</p>
<p>Again thank you for this diary.</p>

