<li id="c320">
  <div class="cx" id="cx51272915">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">Children DON'T invest themselves in their educatio</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1234916/51272915#c320?mode=alone;showrate=1#c320">0+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>education when there is high teacher turn over. &nbsp;It doesn't matter the school. &nbsp;</p>
<p>A friend of mine learned this when he taught in a private Catholic school in NYC. &nbsp;When he started the kids asked if he was going to stay, because they were so used to having teachers leave they didn't want to put in their time, if the teacher wasn't going to commit to them.</p>
<p>He loved the job but ended up leaving after the first year because the pay was so low he could not cover his bills, much less the loans for his education.</p>
<p>Consistency, continuity and relationships are important to children and their education. &nbsp;It doesn't matter the grade.</p>
<p>K-3 where they will have the same teacher all day long, but a different teacher as they move through the grades, provides a "known" when things are shaky in the new year or when things go bad during the year. &nbsp;Do under estimate the power of just being able to wave to someone.</p>
<p>4-8 where a child moves to different classrooms but may have different teachers every year, same thing... plus having someone your older friends or sib had is also less scary and calming (despite possible reports of what an harpy/orge the teacher is .... it's a known)</p>
<p>9-12 where a teen may often have the same teacher through out the years for various classes in history or math, etc. &nbsp; A known, a constant ... you already know what's expected ... you've already developed a relationship.</p>
<p>Consistency, continuity and relationships are actually the argument <strong>FOR</strong> homeschooling . . . especially for itinerant military families.</p>
<p>No teacher's "got this" in their second year, even if they homeschool. &nbsp;Mentor paring programs are essential to teacher development.</p>
<p>This could rightly (also) be seen as another front in class warfare. &nbsp;Expensive private schools brag about their teacher experience, how long they've been doing this, the continuity, etc.</p>
<p>Teacher experience, teacher rention are marks of a healthy school, especially charter and private. &nbsp;</p>
<p>How many professions like "public school teacher" that now require advanced degrees, get so little pay and so little respect?</p>

  </div>
